$ Bash built-in: set -h
@ set -h

`set -h` (default) specifies to remember the executable when it was called.

{ call-foo.sh

  The following script can either be executed with `./call-foo.sh +h` or `./call-foo.sh -h`

  gh|about-Bash|/built-in/set/h/call-foo.sh||

  When executed with `-h`, it prints
code {
hello
foo.sh is hashed (./foo.sh)
hello
foo.sh is hashed (./foo.sh)
code }

  When executed with `+h`, it prints
code {
hello
foo.sh is ./foo.sh
hello
foo.sh is dir/foo.sh
code }

}
{ foo.sh

  gh|about-Bash|/built-in/set/h/foo.sh||

}

